    <section class="mechanism">
      <h2>How L-Theanine Works</h2>
      <p class="mechanism-intro">L-theanine is one of the few amino acids studied for direct effects on brain state. Four mechanisms explain why.</p>
      <div class="mechanism-card">
        <div class="mechanism-points">
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">1.</span>Promotes alpha brain wave activity.</h4><p>L-theanine has been studied for its role in promoting alpha brain wave activity, the brain state associated with calm, focused attention. It's why a cup of green tea feels different from a cup of coffee.</p></div>
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">2.</span>Supports neurotransmitter activity.</h4><p>L-theanine plays a role in supporting GABA, dopamine, and serotonin, the neurotransmitters that influence calm, mood, and motivation.</p></div>
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">3.</span>Counterbalances stimulants.</h4><p>L-theanine works in counterbalance to stimulants like caffeine. Where caffeine increases alertness, L-theanine supports focused attention without the jittery edge.</p></div>
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">4.</span>Supports a calm stress response.</h4><p>L-theanine has been studied for its role in supporting a calm response to stress. It's part of why green tea has long been associated with focused calm rather than the buzz of stronger caffeinated drinks.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="mechanism-footnote">Summarized from published research on L-theanine and cognitive performance.</p>
    </section>

